\section{BEL-rank and spread sets}
\label{sec:spreadsets}

Let $E$ denote the ring of ${{\mathbb{F}}_q}$-endomorphisms of ${\mathbb{F}_{q^n}}$, i.e. $E := {\mathrm{End}}_{{{\mathbb{F}}_q}}({\mathbb{F}_{q^n}})$. Consider a semifield ${\mathbb{S}}$ of order ${\mathbb{F}_{q^n}}$ with centre containing ${{\mathbb{F}}_q}$. Then the set of maps of right-multiplication $R({\mathbb{S}}) := \{R_y:x \mapsto {\mathbb{S}}(x,y)\mid y \in {\mathbb{F}_{q^n}}\}$ define an ${{\mathbb{F}}_q}$-subspace of $E$ in which every nonzero element is invertible. This is known as a {\it semifield spread set}, see \cite{LaPo2011}. Similarly we may use the maps of left-multiplication to define $L({\mathbb{S}}) := \{L_y:x \mapsto {\mathbb{S}}(y,x)\mid y \in {\mathbb{F}_{q^n}}\}$, and then $L({\mathbb{S}}) = R({\mathbb{S}}^d)$. If we work in the projective space ${\mathrm{PG}}(E,q)$, which is isomorphic to ${\mathrm{PG}}(n^2-1,q)$, then the image of $R({\mathbb{S}})$ is known as a {\it geometric spread set}. 

