As before we may define the matrix $M(T)$. We immediately see that $M = c \underline{a}^T \underline{b}$,
i.e. $M_{ij} = a^{q^i}b^{q^j}c$.

This can be extended linearly to obtain a matrix from an algebra corresponding to an arbitrary tensor, namely by defining $M(\sum_i T_i) := \sum_iM(T_i)$, where the $T_i$'s are tensors of rank 1. We will use $T$ to denote both a tensor and its corresponding algebra. This induces a map $T\mapsto M(T)$ from the space ${\mathbb{F}_{q^n}}^{\vee} \otimes {\mathbb{F}_{q^n}}^{\vee} \otimes {\mathbb{F}_{q^n}}$ into ${\mathrm{PG}}(M_n({\mathbb{F}_{q^n}}),{{\mathbb{F}}_q}) \simeq {\mathrm{PG}}(n^3-1,q)$. Denote by $\Omega_0$ the image of the set of fundamental tensors under this map. 

If $\Omega, \Omega'$ are arbitrary sets in a vector (or projective) space, we define as usual the {\it $\Omega$-rank of $\Omega'$} as the minimum number of elements of $\Omega$ needed to span a space containing all elements of $\Omega'$. We denote it by ${\mathrm{rk}}_{\Omega}(\Omega')$. If $\omega$ is a vector (or projective point), we define the {\it $\Omega$-rank of $\omega$} to be the $\Omega$-rank of the singleton set $\{\omega\}$, and denote it by ${\mathrm{rk}}_{\Omega}(\omega)$.

Then the tensor rank of a tensor $T$ is precisely the $\Omega_0$-rank of the point $\langle M(T)\rangle$. This leads to the following relation between tensor rank and matrix rank.

\begin{theorem} For any semifield ${\mathbb{S}}$, it holds that ${\mathrm{trk}}({\mathbb{S}}) \geq {\mathrm{mrk}}({\mathbb{S}})$.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
Denote by $\Omega_1$ the subset of ${\mathrm{PG}}(n^3-1,q)$ induced by the set of rank one matrices in $M_n({\mathbb{F}_{q^n}})$. By Definition \ref{def:mrk}, the matrix rank of ${\mathbb{S}}$ is precisely the $\Omega_1$-rank of $M({\mathbb{S}})$. Clearly $\Omega_0 \subset \Omega_1$, and hence the result follows.
\end{proof}

Since the tensor rank is invariant under isotopy \cite{Lavrauw2011}, the tensor rank of an isotopy class is well defined, and we immediately get the following.
\begin{corollary}For any semifield ${\mathbb{S}}$, it holds that ${\mathrm{trk}}({\mathbb{S}}) \geq {\mathrm{mrk}}([{\mathbb{S}}])$.
\end{corollary}

Given a matrix $A \in M_n({\mathbb{F}_{q^n}})$, we can define an algebra $S_A$ with multiplication $S_A(x,y) = \underline{x}S\underline{y}^T$, as in (\ref{eqn:matalg}). We can then define the isotopy class $[A]$ as the set of matrices in $M_n({\mathbb{F}_{q^n}})$ defining algebras isotopic to $S_A$.

\begin{theorem}
If $T \in V^{\vee} \otimes V^{\vee} \otimes V$, then

\end{theorem}
\begin{proof}
Let $m = \mathrm{max}\{{\mathrm{mrk}}([A]):A \in M_n({{\mathbb{F}}_q})\}$ and $k = {\mathrm{rk}}_{\Omega_0}(\Omega_1)$. Then $T$ is isotopic to an algebra $T'$ with ${\mathrm{rank}}(M(T')) \leq m$. Then $M(T')$ can be written as a sum of at most $m$ elements of $\Omega_1$, and each element of $\Omega_1$ can be written as a sum of at most $k$ elements of $\Omega_0$, and hence ${\mathrm{trk}}(T) = {\mathrm{trk}}(T') \leq mk$, proving the claim.
\end{proof}

This bound is unlikely to be particularly effective. However over finite fields there are no existing good upper bounds on the tensor rank.

\section{Computational results}
\label{sec:comp}
Using the computer classifications from \cite{Demp2008}, \cite{Rua2009},  \cite{Rua2011a}, \cite{Rua2011b}, we calculated the BEL-rank of all known semifields of various orders. We tabulate the results here, and point out some interesting features. Recall that all semifields three dimensional over their centre are fields or generalised twisted fields \cite{Menichetti1977}, and so their BEL-ranks are known. The largest calculation is for semifields of order 64, incidentally giving the most interesting results.



